This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep longer, in an attempt to combat the ever-widening culture of studying throughout the night, stimulated by caffeine.
An academic noted that students at the world's number one university are often clueless as to the basics on how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after making a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
