Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University's health services, claimed that the University decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, showers and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how sports performance affects sleeplessness, and about the importance of maintaining a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
Next, a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that student behavior will not change immediately.
But we think they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in staying up all night still exists, he said, and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure students suffer make sleep deprivation an ever-growing problem.
Making sure to enjoy good quality sleep for long enough should be a “secret weapon” of students to combat stress, tiredness and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode and makes students always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having attended one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
