Saipov, 30, allegedly used a Home Depot rental truck to carry out an attack on a bike path on the West Side Highway, in Lower Manhattan and hit pedestrians and cyclists during his journey, in October.
In order to justify the death penalty, prosecutors must show that Saipov killed the eight victims "intentionally" and that he "intentionally" caused serious personal injuries, according to the notice of intent to seek the death penalty filed in the southern district of New York.
Both crimes could carry a death penalty, according to the court document.
Weeks after the attack, a federal grand jury attacked Saipov with a 22-fault indictment that included eight counts of murder for the benefit of organized crime, which federal prosecutors typically use in mob cases, in addition to a crime of violence and motor vehicle destruction.
Prosecutors claimed that the attack required "considerable planning and premeditation" and described Saipov's manner of acting as "inhumane, cruel and depraved".
"Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov caused injuries, damage and losses to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucco," according to the notice of intent.
Five of the victims were tourists from Argentina.
It has been a decade since the last time the southern district of New York brought a death penalty case to trial.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was convicted of the murder of two drug dealers, but was eventually sentenced to life imprisonment in September 2009.
The last time a death sentence was executed in a federal case in New York was in 1953 for Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a married couple executed after being convicted of conspiracy to carry out espionage actions for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
Both Rosenbergs died in the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
According to court documents, Saipov, a native of Uzbekistan, showed no regret in the days and months following the attack.
Police explained that he told investigators he felt good about what he had done.
According to the indictment, Saipov explained to authorities that he was inspired to carry out the attack after watching ISIS videos on his phone.
According to police, he also requested that the ISIS flag be displayed in his hospital room.
He has pleaded not guilty to the 22-fault indictment.
David Patton, one of the public federal advocates who represented Saipov, claimed they were "obviously disappointed" with the prosecution's decision.
"We believe that the decision to seek the death penalty, rather than accept a plea of guilt and a life sentence without the possibility of freedom, will only prolong the trauma of these events for all the people involved," Patton said.
Saipov's defense team had previously asked prosecutors not to seek the death penalty.
