How the U.S.-China trade war can benefit Beijing
The initial salvoes of the trade war between the US and China were deafening and, although the war does not appear to have to end soon, a distance between the countries may prove beneficial for Beijing in the long run, according to experts.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued his first warning earlier this year, when he imposed taxes on China’s top exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation occurred this week, with new tariffs affecting $200 billion worth of products. These tariffs tax half of all goods arriving in the U.S. from China.
Beijing has increasingly counterattacked in the same way and has recently raised tariffs from five to ten percent for $60 billion of American goods.
China has pledged to replicate the U.S. and the world’s second-largest economy is not likely to turn back anytime soon.
Getting Washington to backtrack involves giving in to some demands, but bowing publicly to the US would be too embarrassing for Xi Jinping, the President of China.
Still, experts say that, if Beijing plays its cards right, the pressures of the trade war with the US could benefit China in the long run by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick policy decision in Washington or Beijing could create the conditions that start a downturn in any of these countries is far more dangerous than witnesses had anticipated,” said Abigail Grace, an Asia-focused research associate at the Center for New American Security, a committee of experts.
Syria is "ready" for refugees to return, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is prepared for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild the country, devastated by a seven-year-old war.
In front of the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said conditions in the country are improving.
"Currently, the situation on the street is more stable and secure, thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas that the terrorists destroyed to restore normality.
All conditions are met for the voluntary return of refugees to the country who had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and their maintenance.
The EU estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the start of the war in 2011.
There are also six million people living in the country who need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem claimed that the Syrian regime appreciates any help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from the countries that funded the insurgency.
The European team wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team has achieved the 2018 Ryder Cup by defeating the US team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National, outside Paris, France.
The U.S. has already lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
The European team again won the crown when Danish captain Thomas Bjorn's team reached the 14.5 points needed to win the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who fought for most of the tournament, threw the kickoff into the water at the par 3 16 hole, which ceded the win to Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari shone in all his series and became one of four players to have achieved the 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament began in 1979.
American Jordan Spieth was set aside with a 5&4 by the least qualified player of the European selection Thorbjorn Olesen, of Denmark.
The world's most qualified player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 and 1 to England's Ian Poulter, who could have played his last Ryder Cup.
The veteran with eight Ryder Cups, Spanish Sergio Garcia, became the biggest winner the tournament has ever had, with 25.5 career points.
