Red Tide Update: Concentrations Drop to Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more dispersed proliferation conditions are being reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier areas, suggesting a lower concentration.
Red tide proliferation extends along approximately 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counts.
Spots can be found 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places, compared to last week's situation.
Red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Average coastal or offshore concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County over the past week, average coastal and offshore concentrations in Hillsborough County, background or upland concentrations in Manatee County, mid-coastal and mid-coastal concentrations in Charlotte County, coastal and offshore background concentrations.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported over the past week in northeast Florida.
